(2, 0, 'testing', '{"0":{"api":"blockchain","static-call":"getdifficulty"},"1":{"api":"weather","configure":{"uri":"\\/wxdata\\/weather\\/local\\/44136","method":"get","query":{"cc":"*","unit":"F","dayf":5}}},"template":{"variables":{"<<GET_DIFFICULTY>>":"blockchain.0.response.body","<<HIGH_TEMP>>":"weather.0.response.body.dayf.day.0.hi"},"css":"","body":"<p>I''m part of the Data Call <b>template data<\\/b>. You can dynamicallygenerate content for your site with templates and variables. Let''s take a gander.<\\/p><p>You see, thegander''s goose loves the small town life, but the gander wishes to fly to Silicone Valley to be a hugesuccess with his new high tech wing booster invention. He already has investors on board who wish to seehis invention boost the flight speed of every goose and gander in the world. If the gander concedes tostay with his goose in their small town, he may find it a bit more difficult to find customers. However,if we take the gander to Silicone Vally, the goose will be very upset. So, what''s good for the goosemight not be good for the gander. Wahh, Wahh... :)<\\/p><p>In other news, below is the output of the Data Call request to BlockChain''s \\"getdifficulty\\" staticcall. It''s shown using a variable, for instance <code><<Variable>><\\/code> or<code>{{Variable}}<\\/code> can signify the place in your template where a variable''s value should go.<\\/p><p>getdifficulty: <<GET_DIFFICULTY>><\\/p><p>Here''s the output for the high temperature for today in Strongsville, OH, our CEO''s home town.<\\/p>High temperature today in fahrenheit: <<HIGH_TEMP>><\\/p>","js":""}}', 1, 3, 0, 0, NULL),
(1, 0, 'custom', '', 1, 3, 0, 0, NULL);